{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":97160,"duration_api_ms":109044,"num_turns":12,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"60f13e87-46d6-4164-bc22-7e054585bf5a","total_cost_usd":0.4808212,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":31470,"cache_read_input_tokens":200362,"output_tokens":2453,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":31470,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":104,"outputTokens":6470,"cacheReadInputTokens":465787,"cacheCreationInputTokens":34848,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.12259270000000003,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":7,"outputTokens":2453,"cacheReadInputTokens":200362,"cacheCreationInputTokens":31470,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.3582285,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Verified all four amendments against the source code. The jitter-exceeds-cap bug (fr-12-0499120d) is confirmed as a real correctness defect in retry_policy.rs. The binary.exists() misclassification (fr-12-42da6128 and fr-12-bff334e0) is a real bug confirmed in process_backend.rs — both amendments describe opposite failure directions of the same Path::exists() check on bare names. The test coverage gap (fr-12-47fc743b) is confirmed: no test for unclean teardown (TransportFailure branch), no jitter range test, and no dedicated confirm_teardown unit test.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-12-47fc743b","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified in the test files. The existing test `spawn_and_wait_timeout_returns_timeout_failure` (process_backend_test.rs:2059) only asserts `FailureClass::Timeout`, which is the clean-teardown path (lines 1064-1065 of process_backend.rs). There is no test exercising the unclean-teardown branch where `confirm_teardown` returns false and the failure is classified as `TransportFailure` (lines 1066-1071). The retry_policy_test.rs backoff test at line 51 uses `with_no_jitter()`, so jitter bounds are never verified. There is no dedicated unit test for the `confirm_teardown` function (process_backend.rs:1509-1516). These are genuine coverage gaps against the stated acceptance criteria."},{"amendment_id":"fr-12-42da6128","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed in source. `resolve_binary` at process_backend.rs:552-553 returns `PathBuf::from(binary_name)` (a bare name like 'claude') when `self.search_paths` is None. At line 1003, the ENOENT handler uses `!binary.exists()` — but `Path::exists()` on a bare name resolves relative to CWD, not PATH. If spawn fails with ENOENT due to a missing working directory or script interpreter (not the binary), and `./claude` doesn't exist in CWD, the check returns false and misclassifies as BinaryNotFound (terminal, max_attempts=1) instead of the retryable TransportFailure. The suggested fix of guarding with `self.search_paths.is_some()` is sound — only trust the exists() check when the binary was resolved to an absolute path."},{"amendment_id":"fr-12-0499120d","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed directly in retry_policy.rs. Lines 122-129 show: `capped = delay.min(self.backoff_cap)` then `Self::apply_jitter(capped)`. The `apply_jitter` function (lines 134-143) multiplies by a factor in [0.75, 1.25). For attempt 5: base=5s, multiplier=16, delay=80s, capped=60s, then jitter can yield up to 60*1.249...=74.9s — exceeding the 60s cap documented at line 33 (`DEFAULT_BACKOFF_CAP_SECS`). The docstring at line 113 says 'capped at backoff_cap' but jitter violates that guarantee. Fix is straightforward: re-cap after jitter with `.min(self.backoff_cap)`."},{"amendment_id":"fr-12-bff334e0","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is the complementary failure direction of the same binary.exists() bug as fr-12-42da6128, confirmed in the same code at process_backend.rs:1003. When `resolve_binary` returns bare name 'claude' and a file `./claude` happens to exist in CWD (a script, config file, or unrelated binary), `binary.exists()` returns true, so the condition `!binary.exists()` is false. The ENOENT handler then falls through to TransportFailure even when the binary is genuinely missing from PATH. This turns a terminal BinaryNotFound (max_attempts=1) into a retryable TransportFailure (max_attempts=5), wasting the full retry budget. Both misclassification directions are valid bugs worth documenting separately."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"c46e9073-c05a-4165-ba49-f488c8f35bd7"}
